*RemindMe!* 5 years Tesla Dumpster fire.

&amp;#x200B;

I have seen this pattern before. Checkout cisco in y2k bubble.

My wife and me over saved to have our first child (Jan 2020), but from Dec 2020 I started actively investing as it was obvious we wouldn't need those savings. It should also be said that my daughter has given me a real focus to put off short term gratification, as my wife and I earned well but spent hard during our 20s (33m and 32f today).

&amp;#x200B;

I basically put everything we had, about £35K in savings and my £3K "poker pot" (casinos are closed, miss the gamble) into stocks. Invested £38K, up £1.2K, enjoying it greatly. Sure beats the 0.6% we were getting from the bank. We will hit £40K by end of March, important as that's the maximum for 2x "ISAs", which are like your IRAs but more generous (£20K max a year, running April to March, means zero tax on capital gains and dividends). 

&amp;#x200B;

Portfolio is fairly safe, but by that I went for what I consider great companies that seemed unloved instead of ETFs / bonds. US wise that was/were JP Morgan, AT&amp;T, Cisco, J&amp;J, PSA, etc. UK wise we're talking Sage, Tesco, Tritax Big Box (my best performer), BP, SSE, etc. I am probably overly diversified, 68 stocks in total, and will be trimming that back aggressively as I did make a few mistakes on reflection. 

&amp;#x200B;

I also grew up poor but my mum got me a bursary into a great school, and I've been lucky / worked hard career wise. I wish I had started investing earlier, but looking to invest pretty hard now with wifey. For me, I am optimistic about the future and humanities abilities to conquer our problems, and so investing just seems an extension of that. I am now super focused on building a retirement fund (aiming at 55) and an inheritance for my daughter that I could only have dreamed of. 

&amp;#x200B;

Wishing you well on your investment journey!

My grandma bought Cisco Systems and rode that shit up to $80.  When the market started to crash, she called her broker and told him to sell.  The fuckface kept telling her it was just a drawdown, and to say in it.  When she finally got him to sell it, it was worthless.  If she had taken people's advice, and held on to it forever, it would be worth $45 today.  That's a total return of like -34% in 20 years, *and* that's the new bubble valuation.  Don't listen to institutional investors tell you that you "can't time the market" or "buy the dip".  They don't have your best interest at heart.

&amp;#x200B;

